data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you inspect the exception and pinpoints exactly which line threw:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName); // bonus: verify details
}
```

**Why?** `[ExpectedException]` has two problems:
1. **Any** line in the test can throw and it still passes — masking bugs.
2. You can't assert on exception properties (message, param name).

`Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` matches the **exact** type. If you also want to catch derived exceptions, use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead.
